To ensure a worst-case or alternative release scenario does not occur, MOSES maintains a release prevention program with the primary focus of protecting plant employees and the public from the hazards associated with an accident or release involving ammonia.  The multifaceted program includes the use of:

( process safety information to document the design basis of the ammonia process equipment;
( process hazards analyses to evaluate the hazards associated with the design basis, installation and operation of the process;
( operating procedures to ensure that the system is operated within the design basis;
( maintenance, inspection and testing procedures to ensure that the system is maintained in accordance with applicable standards and manufacturer's recommendations;
( training, hot work permits, contractor safety and employee participation programs to ensure that all employees and contractors, especially those involved in working on and around the processes, are aware of the hazards, can perform their job duties safely and know the actions to be taken in an emergency;
( management of change and pre-startup safety reviews to ensure that changes to the processes are documented, analyzed and kept within the design basis;
( incident investigation procedure to investigate not only each incident involving a release of ammonia but "near misses" which could have resulted in releases to determine the root causes and make appropriate safety improvements;
( and periodic compliance audits to ensure that the prevention programs in place are adequate and working as they should to protect both employees and the public.
